comments.body:
I tested this fix by setting up a cloud using the following commit ID 

{code}
43ee8e45d2d28f539dad364cc2695e2e07f9c47c
{code}

I did the following before creating a LB

{code}
# euca-modify-property -p loadbalancing.loadbalancer_vm_ntp_server=169.254.169.254
PROPERTY	loadbalancing.loadbalancer_vm_ntp_server	169.254.169.254 was {}

# euca-modify-property -p loadbalancing.loadbalancer_vm_keyname=sshlogin
PROPERTY	loadbalancing.loadbalancer_vm_keyname	sshlogin was {}
{code}

Then I created a LB using EucaLobo and following were the details of the same

{code}
RESERVATION	r-47663CA6	492776843771	euca-internal-492776843771-mylb
INSTANCE	i-30AC3FE3	emi-3604348F	10.104.3.2	172.31.0.11	running	sshlogin	0		m1.small	2013-10-15T08:28:26.295Z	cloud34	eki-A731396A	eri-EFF836AA		monitoring-enabled	10.104.3.2	172.31.0.11			instance-store					paravirtualized		062d09a4-1099-4292-9174-61777b5ec303_cloud34_1				arn:aws:iam::492776843771:instance-profile/internal/loadbalancer/loadbalancer-vm
TAG	instance	i-30AC3FE3	Name	loadbalancer-resources
TAG	instance	i-30AC3FE3	aws:autoscaling:groupName	asg-euca-internal-elb-492776843771-mylb
TAG	instance	i-30AC3FE3	euca:node	172.16.0.1
{code}

I logged inside the ELB using the keypair "sshlogin" and confirmed the content of /etc/ntp.conf which were following:

{code}
driftfile /var/lib/ntp/drift
includefile /etc/ntp/crypto/pw
keys /etc/ntp/keys
restrict 127.0.0.1 
restrict -6 ::1
restrict -6 default kod nomodify notrap nopeer noquery
restrict default kod nomodify notrap nopeer noquery
server 169.254.169.254
{code}

Following was the information on my NTP inside the ELB instance

{code}
[root@ip-172-31-0-11 ~]# ntpq 
ntpq> peers
     remote           refid      st t when poll reach   delay   offset  jitter
==============================================================================
*instance-data   199.102.46.73    2 u   24   64  377    0.131   -0.466   0.674
{code}

Confirmed that it was able to use the IP specified in the CLC property. Looks like when the CLC spins off the ELB instance it passes the property for NTP server IP to the ELB instance as user-data? as it does for the LB keypair property 

If you have any questions please let me know.
